## Context {#context}

This document provides feedback on the [instructlab-knowledge.ipynb](https://github.com/instructlab/examples/blob/main/notebooks/instructlab-knowledge/instructlab-knowledge.ipynb) notebook used for POCs. Ali requested feedback in these areas specifically:

* Does having a modular workflow make sense?  
* Where could UI add value into this workflow?  
* How can we enhance Jupyter notebooks?  
* Usability feedback

I adopted the persona of a Sales Engineer responsible for taking a prospective customer through the POC process. I went through the original CLI-based POC first, and then the notebook-based flow. These are most of the resources I used to get up to speed:

## High-level feedback on the POC experience overall {#high-level-feedback-on-the-poc-experience-overall}

â€”

### Switching context between repos, videos, docs, utilities, notebooks, etc. made the experience feel sluggish {#switching-context-between-repos,-videos,-docs,-utilities,-notebooks,-etc.-made-the-experience-feel-sluggish}

The fact that I am brand new to the product contributed to the friction, but the fact that the materials were scattered around really slowed things down.  
As a Red Hat rep conducting the POC I want to be having the value conversation with my customer not stitching together materials. I want my solution to create the impression that it is part of a powerful platform that solves an entire category of problems. 

Creating a central reference point for the POC materials would reduce friction, enable versioning, and make it almost a self-service experience. For example, this is how [mostly.ai](http://mostly.ai) presents their SDG tutorials:

![][image1]

â€” 

### The POC experience is focused almost exclusively on â€˜howâ€™ and not â€˜whyâ€™ {#the-poc-experience-is-focused-almost-exclusively-on-â€˜howâ€™-and-not-â€˜whyâ€™}

Embedding the value proposition in the POC experience would help motivate users to complete it and provide support for the sales opportunity. Also, the emphasis on Docling is overshadowing the value that Red Hat is bringing as a platform for AI product development. 

For example, this is one of the cell descriptions from the notebook:  
![][image2]

Unless the user has a very specific desire to pipe Docling-generated JSON to another workflow, this description does not provide them with much context about why they should run the cell, or how it relates to the POC. It might be left over from when Conversion and Chunking were in separate notebooks.

A value-oriented description would look more like this:

![][image3]

â€” 

### The notebook creates the impression of being experimental {#the-notebook-creates-the-impression-of-being-experimental}

I completely understand that this is WIP and I **truly appreciate** the access to early work. That said, the notebook has typos, and TODOs, and dead links. It is functional and usable for a POC so it seems like it is ready for some form of stable, MVP release where the distracting WIP stuff is removed. 

Dead links are not the end of the world but they can force a change in the tone of the narrative when presenting. 

â€” 

### It feels like there is a bit too much smooshed into one notebook.  {#it-feels-like-there-is-a-bit-too-much-smooshed-into-one-notebook.}

The review stages especially need a little more room to breathe. I want to be able to validate that the artifacts Iâ€™m generating at each phase are correct and likely to give me great results. 

â€“

## Usability feedback for instructlab-knowledge.ipynb {#usability-feedback-for-instructlab-knowledge.ipynb}

1. This notebook came in an example repo with the directory structure already set. **This is super useful.** For a system that relies so heavily on file names and directory structure, this is a massive upgrade from CLI-based POC flow.

4. This comment is the only guidance I am offered about selecting documents. How do I know how many documents is the correct amount? What is the relation between the number of docs we use for a POC vs. the number of docs we would likely see in a real-world use case? If I am model re-training for use in an agent architecture I think I would want to convert a lot of data, whereas if I am making my chatbot more effective I might only want to convert as many docs as I could manually create qna.yaml files for. Can we offer more guidance?
